		 <tr>
		   <td><font face="verdana" size="2">Just wondering if you or the other programmers were RPG players before you went to work for EQ?  I have notice the Mobs look allot the RPG pictures given in monster manuals for almost all RPGs.  Is this due to those visual conceptions of those original artist or your bosses lack of creativity?
Or are you just constrained to the RPG players conceptions of the mobs in
their minds?  Do you get to free-lance any of the graphics for mobs?  The armors and such have some great details and originality; so I assume you guys are the creative wizards for EQ.<P>

 Sweeney LCpl Sean P
<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>
   It's my understanding that most of the people on the EverQuest Team
have extensive experience with good old-fashioned pencil-'n'-paper
role playing games.  I played Dungeons and Dragons quite a lot as a
kid, and so have Brad McQuaid, Steve Clover, Bill Trost, Kevin Burns,
Ryan Palacio, Sabrina Fox, Geoff Zatkin, and probably a few other
people as well.  Most of us also have a lot of experience with CRPG's. The appearances of EverQuest's monsters are largely determined by
Rick Schmitz, with additional input from Bill, Brad, and of course EQ's
lead artist, Rosie Cosgrove.  The only character that I designed is the
undead dragon, which I pretty much ripped straight from Erol Otus'
drawing of Dragotha on page three of one of my favorite AD&D
modules, White Plume Mountain (dungeon module S2).<P>

   Really, though, there isn't all that much room for creativity when one
is dealing with a well-established library of fictional characters.  If we
get too creative, the game will be less immersive because people will
have too much trouble recognizing creatures that they already know from
Tolkien and D&D and various other mainstays of the fantasy genre.  The
paradox is that we have to come as close as we can to portraying generic
representations of pre-defined characters without actually making them
look generic.  If we were to make, say, a manticore, the compulsory
presence of physical elements like the leonine body, the human head, and
the leathery wings wouldn't leave us much room to go crazy with its look
-- not without our moving too far outside the fantasy "puritanism" that we
believe is a big part of EQ's success.  The more we deviate from the
customary fantasy world, the less our players will feel as though they're
actually in that kind of world, the less they'll feel as though they've
stepped into a real-time D&D module or fantasy novel, and the more
they'll feel as though they're playing another Quake or Unreal or Ultima
Online 2.  I can't speak for my fellow EQ personnel, but I've always
wanted to adventure into the Keep on the Borderlands or the Village
of Hommlet or Lolth's arachnidan ship in real-time in an immersive
fantasy setting; I still can't do that, but EQ is the next best thing.<P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

 GeForce and other such video cards coming out making more polygons available.  I assume this would be a big deal in your line of work. Suppose they tripled the number of polygons you could use, is there any particular place you'd want to spend those?  I'd think hands/feet...<P>

 Ozaak Kaazo
<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   Yes, this is definitely a huge deal in my profession.  Before the
expansion
pack was released, the characters' hands and feet were indeed probably
the most unsatisfactory parts of most of my models; but thanks to an
increase
in the polygon count limit, most of the new Kunark creatures do actually
have
geometry for their digits, so I'm a lot less concerned about that part of
their
anatomy, now.  Currently, I'd like to add triangles to characters' faces
more
than any other parts of their bodies; facial animation does a lot to bring a
character to life, but it requires a lot of polys (or a lot of bitmaps, if
the
polygon limit is insufficient).  After that, I'd like to be able to do more
with
highly malleable elements like clothing and possibly hair.  (I say
*possibly*
hair because the physical nature of hair is probably best dealt with on the
programming level rather than the level of geometric construction.)<P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

 First off I admire the work you have done in EverQuest,  I have a simple question to ask. Out of all the characters you have created, which are you the most proud of creating? (if any)<P>

 A random EQ addict
<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   I can't answer that question until I'm able to visit Kunark from home,
and
who knows when that will be.  I need to relax and play the game outside
the Verant office building in order to fairly evaluate my handiwork, which I
currently cannot do, since for the past month or so, the game gets to the
character select screen without crashing about 3% of the time (and it ain't
my video cards or my drivers -- all of my other games run fine).<P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

 Back in the "Good Old Days" of early EQ, the orc slavers and/or taskmasters wore white shirts. Why do they now wear the same duds as the rest of the orcs? Thanks for your time.<P>

 Chanterelle- An Old, But Well-Preserved Bard
<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   The taskmasters switched shirts to make themselves less distinct
from their garden variety counterparts.  They got tired of being attacked
more often.  No, actually, I have no idea.<P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

 Have you ever considered kicking the 3D modler's asses who made Asheron's Call?  If you haven't, you probably never played AC before.  They look like they were pulled from some poor guys urethra.<P>
 
 Greg
<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   I thought about doing that, but then I asked myself, what does
God need with a starship?<P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

 Hi Milo,<BR>
 Congratulations on your article moving to Everlore.  For me they are a
must read.  Why the move anyway?
 But my primary question is do you favor any 3D card over another inorder
to best view your creations in EQ?<P>

 Thanks.<P>

 Rob
<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>
   I moved to Everlore because the upkeep of Ask Milo at NotCrazy
had become non-existent.  As for my video card preferences, I like
whatever Tom's Hardware Guide likes (<a href="http://www.tomshardware.com">www.tomshardware.com</a>).<P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

 Hey just a quick question. Did you or are you going to help out in the
design of the EQ action figgurs?<--threw that misspelling in for you =) Thanks
for making the great game EverCrack.<P>
<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>
   No way, José.<P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

 I've always been interested in 3D modeling and animation.  I've even done some minor models for a few Quake conversions, though I've used nothing
more complex than a simple modeling program someone wrote for Quake II. (Notwithstanding a few attempts to make use of things like 3D Studio Max
and whatnot.)  I'm interested in learning more about modeling, including what programs you think might be good for a beginner, what books or other resources are the best for teaching the fundamentals, etc.<P>

 I'm not particularly interested in the back side of modeling (that is, coding modeling programs or the math involved), simply with the creation
and animation of models themselves.  Thanks.<P>

 - A non-supermodeller
<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   Several people have put this kind of question to me, and you can
find the answers in Everlore's Ask Milo archives, which will probably
be available by the time this response is posted to the Ask Milo page.<P>

<I>[Editor's Note: We're currently working on having the old Ask Milo archives up by this time next monday or earlier.]</I><P>

